05669nam a22008535i 9781501720130DE-B159720180924034856.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||180924s2018    nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97815017201307 a10.7591/97815017201302doi  a(DE-B1597)496378  a(OCoLC)1012640744  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 7aHIS0480002bisacsh 7aPOL0230002bisacsh 7aSOC0420002bisacsh04a323/.04209592231 aRodan, Garry, eauthor.10aParticipation without Democracy :bContaining Conflict in Southeast Asia /cGarry Rodan. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2018] 4cÂ©2018  a1 online resource   atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations and Acronyms -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: STRUGGLES OVER POLITICAL REPRESENTATION -- t1. THEORIZING INSTITUTIONS OF POLITICAL PARTICIPATION AND REPRESENTATION -- t2. IDEOLOGIES OF POLITICAL REPRESENTATION AND THE MODE OF PARTICIPATION FRAMEWORK -- t3. HISTORY, CAPITALISM, AND CONFLICT -- t4. NOMINATED MEMBERS OF PARLIAMENT IN SINGAPORE -- t5. PUBLIC FEEDBACK IN SINGAPORE'S CONSULTATIVE AUTHORITARIANISM -- t6. THE PHILIPPINES' PARTY-LIST SYSTEM, REFORMERS, AND OLIGARCHS -- t7. PARTICIPATORY BUDGETING IN THE PHILIPPINES -- t8. MALAYSIA'S FAILED CONSULTATIVE REPRESENTATION EXPERIMENTS -- t9. CIVIL SOCIETY AND ELECTORAL REFORM IN MALAYSIA -- tConclusion: CAPITALISM, INSTITUTIONS, AND IDEOLOGY -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex  aOver the past quarter century new ideologies of participation and representation have proliferated across democratic and non-democratic regimes. In Participation without Democracy, Garry Rodan breaks new conceptual ground in examining the social forces that underpin the emergence of these innovations in Southeast Asia. Rodan explains that there is, however, a central paradox in this recalibration of politics: expanded political participation is serving to constrain contestation more than to enhance it.Participation without Democracy uses Rodan's long-term fieldwork in Singapore, the Philippines, and Malaysia to develop a modes of participation (MOP) framework that has general application across different regime types among both early-developing and late-developing capitalist societies. His MOP framework is a sophisticated, original, and universally relevant way of analyzing this phenomenon. Rodan uses MOP and his case studies to highlight important differences among social and political forces over the roles and forms of collective organization in political representation. In addition, he identifies and distinguishes hitherto neglected non-democratic ideologies of representation and their influence within both democratic and authoritarian regimes. Participation without Democracy suggests that to address the new politics that both provokes these institutional experiments and is affected by them we need to know who can participate, how, and on what issues, and we need to take the non-democratic institutions and ideologies as seriously as the democratic ones.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 24. Sep 2018)08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertAsian Studies Contemporary Collection eBook Packagez978311064982608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package 2018z978311066747908iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2018z978311060655308iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018 Englishz978311060425208iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2018z9783110603255oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics and Social Sciences 2018 Englishz978311060401608iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Social Sciences 2018z97831